  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(softwareAppJsonLd)} slot="head" />

  <!-- Desktop sticky TOC in the right sidebar column -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="sidebar" slot="sidebar" />

  <!-- Calculator tool — immediately after intro, visible without scrolling -->
  <NpkCalculator client:load />

  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-500">
    This is the first calculator in the <a href="/clusters/fertilizer-and-nutrients/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Fertilizer & Nutrients cluster</a> — more feeding-rate tools are on the way.
  </p>

  <!-- Mobile TOC accordion — below the calculator, collapsed by default, hidden on desktop -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="accordion" />

  <LeadMagnet variant="full" headline="Get the free Fertilizer & Nutrients Cheat Sheet" clusterTag="fertilizer-cluster" />

  <article class="prose prose-bark mt-8 max-w-none prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-bark-900 prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:scroll-mt-24 prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:font-semibold prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:font-semibold prose-a:text-moss-700 prose-strong:text-bark-900">

    <h2 id="how-do-you-calculate-npk-fertilizer-rates">How Do You Calculate NPK Fertilizer Rates?</h2>
    <p>
      Every fertilizer label shows three numbers, like <strong>10-10-10</strong> or <strong>24-8-16</strong>. These are the percentage, by weight, of <strong>nitrogen (N)</strong>, <strong>available phosphate (P&#8322;O&#8325;, shown as &ldquo;P&rdquo;)</strong>, and <strong>soluble potash (K&#8322;O, shown as &ldquo;K&rdquo;)</strong> in the bag. A 50 lb bag of 10-10-10 contains 5 lb of actual nitrogen (10% of 50), 5 lb of phosphate, and 5 lb of potash &mdash; the rest is filler and carrier material.
    </p>
    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/npk-calculator-fertilizer-bag.svg"
        alt="A fertilizer bag showing N-P-K numbers next to a measuring scoop"
        width="400"
        height="250"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        The three numbers on every bag are percent N, P&#8322;O&#8325;, and K&#8322;O by weight.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Application rates are conventionally expressed as <strong>pounds of actual nitrogen per 1,000 sq ft</strong> &mdash; not pounds of product. That&rsquo;s the standard unit turf and garden guides use, and it&rsquo;s why the calculator above asks for a target N rate rather than a target bag weight: two different fertilizers with different N percentages need very different amounts of <em>product</em> to deliver the same amount of actual nitrogen.
    </p>
    <p>
      For liquid feeding, the equivalent standard is <strong>parts per million (PPM)</strong> of nitrogen in the final solution &mdash; common hydroponic and container-feeding programs target a specific PPM (often 100&ndash;250 for N depending on the crop and growth stage). For blending, the same underlying math applies: you&rsquo;re solving for how much of each product delivers your target absolute amount of N, P, and K, in the right proportion. All of this is an estimate that should be adjusted based on plant response and, ideally, a current soil test &mdash; it is not a substitute for lab-based recommendations.
    </p>
    <p>
      A quick visual check before reaching for fertilizer: <strong>yellowing leaves</strong> (especially older, lower leaves that yellow while newer growth stays green) are a classic sign of <strong>nitrogen deficiency</strong>, since the plant scavenges N from older tissue to feed new growth. A <strong>purple or reddish tint</strong> on leaf undersides, stems, or the whole plant &mdash; particularly in cool weather or on seedlings &mdash; often points to <strong>phosphorus deficiency</strong>, which blocks the pigment pathway. These visual cues are a useful starting signal, not a diagnosis: other causes (cold stress, root damage, certain diseases) can produce similar symptoms, so confirm with a soil test before correcting.
    </p>

    <h2 id="common-fertilizer-application-rates">Common Fertilizer Application Rates</h2>
    <p>
      General starting-point ranges for actual nitrogen. Always defer to a current soil test or product label where available &mdash; these are typical ranges, not prescriptions for your specific soil.
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-left text-sm not-prose">
        <caption class="mb-3 text-left text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-bark-400">
          Common Nitrogen Application Rates by Use
        </caption>
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b-2 border-moss-200 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-bark-500">
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 pr-4 font-semibold">Use</th>
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 pr-4 font-semibold">Rate (lb N / 1,000 sq ft)</th>
            <th scope="col" class="py-2.5 font-semibold">Frequency</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-bark-700">
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Established lawn (maintenance)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">0.5&ndash;1 lb per application</td>
            <td class="py-2">2&ndash;4 applications/year (2&ndash;4 lb/year total)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50 bg-moss-50/30">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">New lawn (at seeding)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">~1 lb, plus starter P</td>
            <td class="py-2">Once, at seeding</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Vegetable garden (pre-plant)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">1&ndash;2 lb</td>
            <td class="py-2">Once before planting, plus side-dressing</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-moss-50 bg-moss-50/30">
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Established trees &amp; shrubs (root zone)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">1&ndash;3 lb</td>
            <td class="py-2">Annually, over the root zone area</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row" class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-bark-900">Containers / hydroponic feed (liquid)</th>
            <td class="py-2 pr-4">100&ndash;250 PPM N</td>
            <td class="py-2">Every watering or per feeding schedule</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 id="worked-example-application-rate">Worked Example: Application Rate</h2>
    <p>
      Let&rsquo;s size a <strong>10-10-10</strong> bag for a <strong>5,000 sq ft lawn</strong> at a target of <strong>1 lb actual N per 1,000 sq ft</strong>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Total N needed:</strong> 1 lb &times; (5,000 &divide; 1,000) = <strong>5 lb of actual nitrogen</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Fertilizer needed:</strong> 5 lb &divide; (10 &divide; 100) = <strong>50 lb of 10-10-10</strong>.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      So a 5,000 sq ft lawn needs <strong>50 lb of 10-10-10</strong> to deliver 1 lb of actual N per 1,000 sq ft. That same 50 lb also delivers 5 lb of P&#8322;O&#8325; and 5 lb of K&#8322;O, since all three percentages are equal in a 10-10-10 product &mdash; with an unbalanced fertilizer like 24-8-16, the phosphate and potash delivered would scale differently.
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example-liquid-fertilizer-dilution">Worked Example: Liquid Fertilizer Dilution</h2>
    <p>
      Say you have a <strong>10-10-10 liquid concentrate</strong> and want to feed at <strong>150 PPM nitrogen</strong> &mdash; a common general-purpose houseplant and container strength &mdash; mixed up in a <strong>2-gallon</strong> watering can.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Rate needed:</strong> 150 &divide; (10 &times; 74.9) = <strong>~0.20 oz of concentrate per gallon</strong> of water.</li>
      <li><strong>Total for a 2-gallon container:</strong> 0.20 oz &times; 2 = <strong>~0.4 oz of concentrate</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Check:</strong> 0.20 oz/gal &times; 10% N &times; 74.9 = <strong>150 PPM</strong> &mdash; confirms the math.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      So for a 2-gallon can at 150 PPM N, you&rsquo;d measure out roughly <strong>0.4 oz</strong> of the 10-10-10 concentrate. That&rsquo;s a small enough amount that a syringe or a marked measuring cap &mdash; the kind that ships with most liquid concentrates &mdash; is far more accurate than trying to eyeball a fraction of an ounce in a kitchen measuring spoon. If you wanted a stronger feed for a heavy-feeding vegetable instead, say 250 PPM, the same fertilizer would need about 0.33 oz per gallon (0.67 oz for the 2-gallon can) &mdash; the calculator&rsquo;s liquid mode recalculates this instantly for any target PPM, container size, or fertilizer strength.
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example-blending-two-fertilizers">Worked Example: Blending Two Fertilizers</h2>
    <p>
      Say you have <strong>Urea (46-0-0)</strong> and a <strong>10-10-10</strong> complete fertilizer on hand, and want to approximate a <strong>3-1-2 ratio</strong> (a common lawn-program target) over that same 5,000 sq ft at 1 lb N/1,000 sq ft.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Targets:</strong> 5 lb N, 1.67 lb P (5 &times; 1&frasl;3), 3.33 lb K (5 &times; 2&frasl;3).</li>
      <li><strong>Solving for N and P exactly:</strong> ~7.25 lb Urea + ~16.67 lb of 10-10-10 hits 5 lb N and 1.67 lb P precisely.</li>
      <li><strong>Check K:</strong> that combination only supplies 16.67 &times; 10% = <strong>1.67 lb K</strong> &mdash; short of the 3.33 lb target.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      The calculator flags this automatically: with only these two products, you cannot hit a 3-1-2 ratio exactly, because neither product supplies extra potassium without also changing the N and P amounts. Adding a third, potassium-only product (like muriate of potash, 0-0-60) makes an exact match solvable &mdash; the calculator&rsquo;s 3-product blend mode handles that case directly.
    </p>

    <LeadMagnet variant="compact" clusterTag="fertilizer-cluster" />

    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Confusing the three numbers.</strong> N-P-K percentages are not interchangeable, and none of them is "the fertilizer strength" on its own &mdash; each governs a different nutrient with a different role (N for leaf growth, P for roots/flowers, K for overall plant health and stress tolerance).</li>
      <li><strong>Over-applying nitrogen.</strong> More N doesn&rsquo;t mean more growth past the plant&rsquo;s ability to use it &mdash; excess nitrogen leaches into groundwater, burns roots at high concentrations, and can push soft, disease-prone growth. Stick to the recommended rate range. If your total seasonal N is, say, 3 lb per 1,000 sq ft, <strong>split it into 2&ndash;3 lighter applications</strong> spaced a few weeks apart rather than applying it all at once: plants get a steadier nutrient supply, uptake is more efficient, and the risk of fertilizer burn drops significantly.</li>
      <li><strong>Applying fertilizer right before heavy rain.</strong> Water moves fertilizer into the root zone, but a heavy downpour can carry soluble nutrients &mdash; especially nitrogen &mdash; straight off the surface and into storm drains before the soil absorbs them. That&rsquo;s wasted product and a pollution problem. Check the forecast and skip the application if more than about half an inch of rain is expected within 24 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping the watering-in step.</strong> Most granular fertilizers sit inert on the soil surface until water dissolves and carries them into the root zone. After applying, water with roughly <strong>&frac14; to &frac12; inch</strong> (or let light rain do it) so nutrients actually reach the roots and start working. Skipping this step leaves fertilizer sitting on leaves and dry soil, where it can burn foliage and never benefit the plant.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring soil test results.</strong> A soil test might show you already have adequate or excess phosphorus, in which case a high-P starter fertilizer is wasted money and, in some states, restricted by law near waterways. Test before you guess.</li>
      <li><strong>Using lawn rates for vegetables (or vice versa).</strong> Turf and vegetable gardens have different nutrient demand curves and different tolerance for salt buildup from fertilizer. Match the rate to the crop, not just to what&rsquo;s in the shed.</li>
      <li><strong>Assuming any two fertilizers can hit any target ratio exactly.</strong> As the blending example above shows, two arbitrary products usually cannot be combined to hit an arbitrary target ratio precisely &mdash; the math only works out for specific combinations. A third, complementary product (or accepting an approximation) is often required.</li>
    </ul>

    <FAQBlock id="npk-calculator-faq" heading="NPK Calculator FAQ" faqs={faqs} />

    <LeadMagnet variant="compact" clusterTag="fertilizer-cluster" />

    <h2 id="sources-and-further-reading">Sources &amp; further reading</h2>
    <p>
      Application rate conventions and nutrient recommendation guidance in this article draw on the USDA Natural Resources Conservation Service&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/sites/default/files/2023-06/EC750_2023.pdf" rel="noopener">Fertilizer Recommendations Guide</a>. For more on how we build and verify the formulas behind every calculator on this site, see our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <RelatedCalculatorsList id="related-calculators" items={[
      { name: 'Fertilizer & Nutrients cluster', url: '/clusters/fertilizer-and-nutrients/', anchorText: 'Fertilizer & Nutrients cluster', note: 'more feeding and nutrient calculators as this cluster grows.' },
      { name: 'Grass Seed Calculator', url: '/calculators/grass-seed-calculator/', note: 'starting a new lawn? Figure out seed first, then use this to plan your starter fertilizer.' },
      { name: 'Raised Bed Soil Calculator', url: '/calculators/raised-bed-soil-calculator/', note: 'filling a new bed? Get your soil volume right before you fertilize it.' },
    ]} />

    <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-bark-500">
      Last updated: {formattedDate}.
    </p>
  </article>
</CalculatorLayout>
